      <%# steps %>
      <div class="bg-stone-50 pt-24 pb-0">
        <%# Section 1 %>
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl flex flex-row items-center px-6 lg:px-8 mb-14">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <!-- Ensure all images are the same width -->
            <img src=<%= image_path 'gateways.jpg' %> alt="" class="w-64 h-auto object-cover">
          </div>
          <div class="ml-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-600">Gateway's</h2>
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-700">
              The Gateway's beacon serves as a Proof of Coverage (PoC) using LoRaWAN technology for location verification purposes. The beacons communicate and prove their geographical positions relative to one another.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <%# Section 2 %>
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl flex flex-row items-center px-6 lg:px-8 mb-14">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <!-- Ensure all images are the same width -->
            <img src=<%= image_path 'IoT.jpg' %> alt="IoT sensor" class="w-64 h-auto object-cover">
          </div>
          <div class="ml-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-600">IoT Sensors</h2>
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-700">
              Tracking sensors beacon to this network and must be within a short distance of LoraWAN gateways in order for the gateways to pick up the beacon signals.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <%# Section 3 %>
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl flex flex-row items-center px-6 lg:px-8 mb-14">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <!-- Ensure all images are the same width -->
            <img src=<%= image_path 'topolbot.png' %> alt="topolbot" class="w-64 h-auto object-cover">
          </div>
          <div class="ml-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-600">Oracle Data</h2>
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-700">
              Each gateway that receives the sensor's transmission supplies it to the LoRaWAN network for verification. The LoRaWAN network eventually forwards it to the pol.bot oracle, along with the received signal strength (RSSI), signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), and proven latitude/longitude of the gateway.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <%# Section 4 %>
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl flex flex-row items-center px-6 lg:px-8 mb-14">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <!-- Ensure all images are the same width -->
            <img src=<%= image_path 'trilat.jpg' %> alt="trilateration" class="w-64 h-auto object-cover">
          </div>
          <div class="ml-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-600">Trilateration</h2>
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-700">
              The pol.bot oracle determines the sensor's relative location based on the received signal strength at each gateway. A radius around each gateway, indicating where the IoT sensor could have transmitted from, is used along with a form of trilateration or multilateration.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <%# Section 5 %>
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl flex flex-row items-center px-6 lg:px-8 mb-0">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <!-- Ensure all images are the same width -->
            <img src=<%= image_path 'on_blockchain.png' %> alt="on_blockchain" class="w-64 h-auto object-cover">
          </div>
          <div class="ml-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-600">Distributed Ledger</h2>
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-700">
              The pol.bot oracle records the device's location data on the ledger within a <a href="https://hashscan.io/testnet/contract/0.0.3643101" class="text-base text-stone-500 hover:text-stone-900 underline" target="_blank">Smart Contract</a>. Placing the location data on-chain renders it auditable and actionable through the Smart Contract's getLocation and isDeviceWithinDistance functions.            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <%# Add more sections as needed, following the same pattern %>
      </div>
      <%# Frequently Asked Questions %>
      <div class="sm:py-16 lg:py-12">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl divide-y divide-stone-200/10 px-6 py-0 sm:py-0 lg:px-8 lg:py-0">
          <%# < %>
          <dl class="mt-10 space-y-8 divide-y divide-stone-200/10">
            <div class="pt-8 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-12 lg:gap-8">
              <dt class="text-base font-semibold leading-7 text-lime-800 lg:col-span-5">What payment methods do you accept?</dt>
              <dd class="mt-4 lg:col-span-7 lg:mt-0">
                <p class="text-base leading-7 text-stone-800">Through your Hashpack wallet. For more information on how to create a Hashpack Wallet visit: <a href="https://www.hashpack.app/download" class="text-lime-800 underline hover:text-stone-400" target="_blank">https://www.hashpack.app/download</a></p>
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="pt-8 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-12 lg:gap-8">
              <dt class="text-base font-semibold leading-7 text-lime-800 lg:col-span-5">How is the location so accurately tracked?</dt>
              <dd class="mt-4 lg:col-span-7 lg:mt-0">
                <p class="text-base leading-7 text-stone-800">We use a global network of LoraWAN gateways. These gateways regularly prove their coverage (PoC) to each other, thus proving their geolocation on a global map. Tracking sensors beacon to this network using LoraWAN. These sensors must be within a short distance of these LoraWAN gateways in order for the gateways to pick up the beacon signals. Every gateway within "earshot" receive the beacon and forward it on to our pol.bot Oracle. The Oracle then determines the possible location of the sensor based on the received signal strength at each gateway. This allows us to determine a radius of where the IoT sensor transmitted from using a form of trilateration or multilateration.</p>
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="pt-8 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-12 lg:gap-8">
              <dt class="text-base font-semibold leading-7 text-lime-800 lg:col-span-5">What level of accuracy can be expected?
              </dt>
              <dd class="mt-4 lg:col-span-7 lg:mt-0">
                <p class="text-base leading-7 text-stone-800"> We use a simplified approach to estimate the sensor's location based on the received signal strength indication (RSSI) and signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) from multiple gateways picking up the transmission from the nearby IoT device. Our approach doesn't provide exact coordinates but can determine if the IoT device transmitted within a defined radius of the gateways that received the transmitted beacon.</p>
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="pt-8 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-12 lg:gap-8">
              <dt class="text-base font-semibold leading-7 text-lime-800 lg:col-span-5">How scalable is the service?</dt>
              <dd class="mt-4 lg:col-span-7 lg:mt-0">
                <p class="text-base leading-7 text-stone-800">Proof of location is stored in our custom Smart Contracts on any EVM compatible ledger. The only ledger supported currently is Hedera, because of it's impressive TPS numbers to keep up with a high volume of IoT device messages.</p>
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
          <!-- More questions... -->
        </div>
      </div>
